Biological Background

The basal actinopterygian Polypterus senegalus is an amphibious fish that has been observed to demonstrate phenotypic plasticity in its pectoral fins between individuals raised in aquatic versus terrestrial environments. The pectoral fins are a key component that determine the locomotion and support the body to âwalkâ. However, there is limited knowledge on the phenotypic changes that may occur to facilitate locomotion differences between terrestrial versus aquatic groups. Within Polypterus, there is growing evidence of phenotypic plasticity between these two groups within locomotive action (Standen et al.Â 2016) as well as anatomical character of the pelvic girdle elements (Standen et al.Â 2014). Further quantification of structural differences in the anatomical system which facilitates this difference in locomotive capacity may provide direct evidence of phenotypic plasticity that may have allowed early amphibians to succeed in the late Devonian terrestrial invasion.

This project will focus on one metric (bone density) of the skeletal features in Polypterus to begin to address the overall question of whether phenotypes between aquatically-raised versus terrestrially-raised individuals are significantly different. This bone density data was collected for five different skeletal elements of Polypterus fin rays: Propterygia, metapterygia, radials, proximal fin rays (hemitrichia), and distal fin rays (hemitrichia). Organization of this data, described below, allows for preliminary analysis through bone density of the following questions: 1. Is overall bone density significantly different individuals raised aquatically versus terrestrially (overall and within specific bone groups)? 2. Is there significant difference in bone density between anterior (ventral) and posterior (dorsal) bone elements (overall and between treatments)? 3. Is there a significant difference in bone density between proximal versus distal bone elements (overall, between treatments, and within fin rays)?

As more bone density data remains to be collected for this thesis, this project will provide a preliminary basis for further analysis on bone density analysis. Further, looking forward, several other points of analysis will be included in evaluating phenotypic plasticity in Polypterus overall. Since the pectoral fins of terrestrial Polypterus are high load-bearing points of contact on the surface medium, the physical character between terrestrial and aquatic individuals may differ. Other studies have made compelling links from physical characteristics (flexural capacity) to mechanical capacity of other fish fins (Sahil et al.Â 2018, Das 2023); The flexural modulus of Polypterus pectoral fins will be compared between terrestrial and aquatic groups later in this thesisâs progression as a proxy of phenotypic plasticity. Further, the morphologies and geometries of pectoral fin rays in aquatically mobile versus benthic taxa have been shown to demonstrate significant differences (Taft 2011), and within benthic species dorsal/ventral positioning of fin rays creates significant morphological variation due to difference in substrate interaction (Taft & Taft 2012), inviting additional anaylsis of plasticity in Polypterus fin geometries and morphologies. similar to what has been seen in their clavicals in particular (Standen et al.Â 2014).

Differences in these measurements between these two groups might indicate that phenotypic plasticity in pectoral fins may have allowed for improved ability for terrestrial locomotion and innovation in amphibious fish during the terrestrial invasion. To begin, this project will utilize the data currently available on bone density to begin to evaluate this comparison.

The Data

The data set used in this project covers the bone density data for 10 individual specimens: five raised aquatically (essentially as a ânormalâ fish in a fish tank), and five raised terrestrially (mostly on dirt with a couple of shallow ponds). For each individual specimen the propterygia, metapterygia, radials, proximal fin rays, and distal fin rays were measured. For the propterygia, metapterygia, radials, and proximal fin rays, five bone density measurements were taken around the mid-length of each bone. There were usually fourteen radials, although sometimes thirteen and fifteen were observed. For each individual, five anterior and five posterior rays were measured (at mid-length, five measurements each). The same five anterior and posterior rays were measured for distal fin rays, although, instead of five measurements at mid-length, five measurements were taken across the proximal-distal axis, starting immediately after the first joint in each ray, and extending towards the termination of the ray, capturing the bone density trends radiating distally and outwards from jointing with the radials.

These measurements were taken in ImageJ software using the light intensity from CT-scans of the whole individual fish. Included within each scan were four hydroxyapatite rods with standardized densities. Therefore, for each scan (each of which had varying brightnesses and light intensities) the intensities of these hydroxyapatite rods could be measured and regressed to their known densities. This regression could then be applied to any light intensity data that was measured for the target bones described above. This strategy allows for consistent and reliable quantification of bone densities from CT-scan data. An example of the creation of one of these csv files is shown below.

regressionHAS <- function(file_path) {
  
  d1 <- read.csv(file_path, header = TRUE)
  colnames(d1) <- c('group', 'values')
  d1$values <- as.numeric(d1$values)
  n_group <- nrow(d1) %/% 5
  
  means <- sapply(1:n_group, function(i) {mean(d1$values[((i-1)*5+1):(i*5)])})
  print(means)
  
  ex_var <- c(-20.379, 101.8616, 212.4351, 417.3955, 789.2673)
  matrix <- matrix(c(means, ex_var), nrow=2, byrow=TRUE)

rownames(matrix) <- c("Intensity Measured", "HA Vals")
print(matrix)

plot(means, ex_var, ylab="Density Standards", xlab="Measured Intensity")
mod <- lm(ex_var ~ means)
abline(mod)
print(summary(mod))
}

intenseregression <- function(incsv, outcsv, m, b) {
  
  
  ndata <- read.csv(incsv, header = TRUE)
  
  
  ndata$y <- m * ndata$x + b
  
  
  write.csv(ndata, outcsv, row.names = FALSE)
  
  
  print(paste("New data:", outcsv))
}

This calibrated bone density data would be produced as a single column csv file for a specific bone element, with important dorsal/ventral and proximal/distal positioning information held within the single column of the variable âBone Densityâ for each file. For example, all radial files were measured from dorsal-most to ventral-most, so in an individual with fourteen radials measured five times each, the first five rows of the column represent the first most dorsal radial, and the last five rows represent the most ventral radial for a total of seventy rows. All individual csv files, then, had to be aggregated into a single data set covering the measurements for all ten individuals. The code for this data conglomeration is shown below. Within the data set, the variables Specimen (denoting the specific individual), Treatment (aquatic vs.Â terrestrial), Bone.Group (radials, proximal radials, etc.), Position (Dorsal vs Ventral, Proximal vs Distal), and BoneDensity (mg/ccm) are listed.

Aggregation of the code from individual specimen and bone group csv files used the following code, which organized files by bone groups (from the file names) before putting them through a function which categorizes any given input file by Specimen.ID, Treatment Group, and Bone Group (along with associated densities), and collects it into a single csv file using rbind:

path_to_data <- "C:/Users/Luke Friedman/Documents/Polypterus"

specimen_ids <- list( Aquatic = c("A2", "A3", "B4", "B5", "C2"), Terrestrial = c("bluered", "gror", "orgwht", "redblue", "redred"))

# Bone groups
bone_groups <- list(
  Radials = list(filename_suffix = "Radials.csv"),
    
  Proximal_Fin_Rays = list(filename_suffix = "proxrays.csv"),
  Distal_Fin_Rays = list(filename_suffix = "distrays.csv"),
  Prop_Metap = list(filename_suffix = "PrMt.csv")
)

process_csv <- function(file_path, bone_group, specimen_id, treatment_group = list()) {
  data <- read.csv(file_path)
  
  if ("Density" %in% colnames(data)) {
    bone_density <- data[["Density"]]
  } else {
    bone_density <- data[[3]]
  }
  
  if (is.null(bone_density) || length(bone_density) == 0) {
    warning(paste("No valid bone density data found in file:", file_path))
    return(NULL)
  }
  
  processed_data <- data.frame(
    Specimen.ID = specimen_id,
    Treatment.Group = treatment_group,
    Bone.Group = bone_group,
    BoneDensity = bone_density
  )
  
  return(processed_data)
}


all_data <- data.frame()
for (treatment in names(specimen_ids)) {
  for (specimen in specimen_ids[[treatment]]) {
    for (bone_group in names(bone_groups)) {
      file_path <- file.path(path_to_data, paste0(specimen, "_", bone_groups[[bone_group]]$filename_suffix))
      
      if (!file.exists(file_path)) {
        warning(paste("File not found:", file_path)) }
      
        bone_data <- process_csv(
          file_path = file_path,
          bone_group = bone_group,
          specimen_id = specimen,
          treatment_group = treatment
        )
          all_data <- rbind(all_data, bone_data)}}}

output_file_path <- file.path(path_to_data, "consolidated_bone_density_data1.csv")
write.csv(all_data, file = output_file_path, row.names = FALSE)
cat("Final data saved to:", output_file_path, "\n")

Methods

Describe the questions you posed and the methods used to address them. State the assumptions underlying the methods (e.g.Â normal distribution of residuals in most parametric tests and linear regressions) and demonstrate or discuss whether they are satisfied by your data, for example by visualizing the data in some form.

As described above, the first overarching question for this data was, âIs overall bone density significantly different individuals raised aquatically versus terrestrially (overall and within specific bone groups)?â.

Before answering this question the data was visualized to understand its distribution using the code below. As seen in the first histogram and density plot. The raw data shows a massive range of bone density values, from <300 mg/ccm to over 20,000 mg/ccm. This is not only unexpected for bone densities in the fins of fish of the same species, but is almost certainly the result of some measurement error. To better understand the source of these unexpected bone density values, the density plot was log-transformed, revealing a relatively strong division of two main density groups which create the bimodal distribution seen below. To find the source of this second high-value group, the data was first divided into bone group with the logic that perhaps a certain bone group demonstrated a particularly high bone density compared to the rest. This was not the case as shown by the retained bimodal distribution in the faceted density plots. Similarly, dividing the data into dorsal versus ventral positioning resulted in continued bimodal distributions, again suggesting that this positioning was not the source of the extreme values.

Results

Taking this somewhat-normally distributed data, analysis of the questions outlined above was done, using both the filtered (excluding the three outlying individuals) as well as the unfiltered (including the three outlying) data to maintain consistency in case later analysis shows that somehow the data of these three individuals is in fact accurate. To begin to analyze the overall bone density between treatments overall and within different bone groups, a standard t test was applied to both the unfiltered and filtered data sets, visualized by the error plots shown below (note the different y axis values between the two). As shown, the difference in overall bone density across bone groups between the two treatments (aquatic versus terrestrial) is insignificant in the unfiltered data containing the outlying individuals (p-value=0.3606), while the difference between treatments overall in filtered data is significant (p-value=0.006643). Testing for the robustness of these results through bootstrap reâsampling with replacement demonstrates the robustness of this result without bonferroni correction as visualized in the histograms below for 1000 replications with resampling. With bonferroni correction no p-values out of 1000 show significance in unfiltered data, while only 88 (8.8%) show significance in filtered data. This does imply that there is some significance in the difference in treatment values post-adjustment, although the effect might be more modest than is initially presented in the histograms.

Overall, these results imply a relatively robust relationship between treatment group and overall bone density in filtered data, although the bonferroni adjustment results suggests caution in assigning high strength to this relationship overall. Regardless, there is indication that overall bone densities in the fins of individuals between aquatic and terrestrial treatments might experience a difference in bone density across the bone groups within the fin itself. However, this may be impacted by a particular bone group more so than others.

get_p_value_t_test <- function() {
  resamp <- hist1 %>% sample_frac(1, replace = TRUE)
  tresults <- t.test(BoneDensity ~ Treatment.Group, data = resamp, var.equal = TRUE)
  return(tresults$p.value)
}
set.seed(123)
pvalues <- replicate(n = 1000, expr=get_p_value_t_test())
sig <- sum(pvalues < 0.05)

Similar bootstrapping with re sampling with replacement for each of the bone groups shows similar robustness in un-adjusted histograms, while bonferroni adjustment again shows 0 counts of significant results in unfiltered data, and 40-50/1000 (4-5%) significant results in filtered data. This again suggests some strength in the relationship between treatment groups within specific bone groups, although to a lesser extent than overall across bone groups. Overall these analyses show some points of significant difference in bone density both overall across bone groups and within groups (particularly within distal fin rays and radials), which invite further investigation into these particular comparisons with more data later on.

}

The second question of this project was, âIs there significant difference in bone density between anterior (ventral) and posterior (dorsal) bone elements (overall and between treatments)?â. The rationale behind this question is that polypterus using their pectoral fins for load support use the anterior (ventral) portion of their fins to interact with the substrate on which they are âwalkingâ is in, and therefore these regions might demonstrate higher bone densities to compensate for this higher physical stress.

To evaluate this question each bone group was separated out, and averaged by individual element with the group. Starting with radials, the first plot shows boxplots for each individually numbered radial across treatments, with radial 1 being most dorsal and radial 15 being most ventral. Filtered data in the second plot seems to begin to show an upward trend in bone density moving from dorsal to ventral positioning. This was tested using a linear regression with first the averages from each individual (R-squared: 0.2306, p-value: 5.613e-7), then condensed to the averages across individuals for each individual radial. The regression for this plot gave an R-squared value of 0.5903 and p-value of 8.2e-4. Next, since only 2 individuals were observed with a 15th radial, this 15th radial was removed to better capture the average fin, shown in the third regression plot (R-squared: 0.9076, p-value: 1.465e-7). Comparing these results to unfiltered data averaged by radial number (R-squared: .2634, p-value: 0.035), it is clear that even without tweaking the data for better trend representation the filtered data assigns much higher explanatory power to radial number (dorsal/ventral positioning) compared to unfiltered data, while regardless there is apparent explanatory power in positioning along this axis for bone density within radials.

Propterygium and Metapterygium: For the propterygium (more dorsal) and metapterygium(more ventral), since there are only two bones to be compared, a linear regression can not be done, although from the scatter plots below there seemed to be some difference between the two, so a t-test comparing the means of these two groups was applied. Shown below, the p-value for filtered data was 0.3763 (t=-0.92), while the unfiltered data showed p=0.8046 and t=-0.25. This demonstrates little statistical significance in difference in density between these two bone elements, and therefore little difference on the dorsal-ventral axis.

Finally, differences in bone density within bone group between treatment groups was completed (this time only using filtered data). Visualizations show little difference in intercept or slope except for distal fin rays, which show significantly different intercepts (similar slopes) between treatment groups. This is confirmed by linear regression data, which shows no statistical significance by treatment (intercept difference) or interaction between treatment and bone number (slope) for radials or proximal fin rays, but a significant p-value for the treatment (intercept) for distal fin rays (0.000717), as shown in the linear regression tables below. This demonstrates both that for most bone groups treatment does not have a significant effect on bone density in terms of dorsal-ventral positioning, and further does not impact the rate of bone density change along this axis (which would be seen in the interaction between treatment and bone number), except for the strong effect of treatment on bone density along this axis in only distal fin rays, which might be due to their distal positioning in the fin, and therefore higher stress via interactions with substrates for walking.

This leads to the final question: Is there a significant difference in bone density between proximal versus distal bone elements (overall, between treatments, and within fin rays)? Previous studies have found in other benthic fish fins strong evidence of morphological differences along the proximal-distal axis is fish fin rays (Taft 2011, Taft & Taft 2012), suggesting there might be notable differences within particular bones. First visualization and analysis was conducted across all bone groups arranged from most proximal to most distal. Using filtered data, mean bone density values per bone group and between treatments were calculated and plotted, and then analyzed using linear regression since they are arranged from proximal to distal positioning in the fin. If there was significant difference in density along this axis across bone groups overall, the linear regression should mark statistical significance. This is not the case, however, with no significant explanatory power for either target variable and poor p-values in the linear regression. Further, comparison between treatments also shows no statistical significance (p=0.7894). This leaves analysis within specific bone groups. However since only distal fin rays had measurements that varied along the proximal/distal axis (other bone groups only had measurements at mid-length of each bone), only distal fin rays can be analyzed.

Shown below is the bone density of distal fin rays along the proximal-distal axis between treatment groups, demonstrating visually striking differences. Statistically, using an anova test, both proximal-distal positioning (p-value=1.1e-6) and treatment (p-value=4.46e-13) show strong differences in bone density. Not only are the treatment groups distinct, but the terrestrial treatment shows the higher bone densities, which aligns with the hypothesis that terrestrial rearing induces increased bone density as a phenotypic reaction to a change in fin use. This is an exciting result, which will hopefully be bolstered by the addition of new data soon.

Conclusions

Add a few paragraphs to describe what you learned and what new questions have been raised by your results. What do you plan to do next?

Across these analyses, overall bone density seems to be significantly different between treatment groups, as well as within distal fin rays and radials. Further, across all bone groups and treatments there is relatively clear indication that bone density varies consistently across the dorsal-ventral axis, with higher densities occuring ventrally where more loading stress seems to occur observing active locomotion in terrestrial Polypterus. Trends along this axis do not seem to vary significantly between treatment groups, however, contradicting the assumption that terrestrial fin use might impact these trends. Perhaps fin use while swimming is disproportionately impacted in ventral positions, which also carries over to terrestrial use as described? Further, there seems to be little significance in proximal-distal position trends by bone group overall, while there is very strong evidence for proximal-distal trends in distal rays overall and differences by treatment.

Overall some of these patterns in bone density may help to explain the plasticity of locomotion and phenotypes in amphibious Polypterus. However, this study is limited both by the number of samples used so far (which was worsened by the three individuals removed in the filtered data for highly outlying density values), as well as the degree of significance of bone density in overall fin function and phenotypic expression. For these reasons, looking forward, the three specimens which presented outlying densities will be re-measured, and at least 2 additional individuals will be added to increase the power of these analyses. Then, apart from bone density, this thesis project plans to include geometrical analyses of bone elements as well as physical stiffness testing (youngâs modulus) to increase the breadth of measurements and analyses in making inferences on phenotypic plasticity in these Polypterus fins.
